"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144752","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-09-09","<p>The decommissioning of Abercorn Barracks was announced in the Better Defence Estate announcement of 7 November 2016 (Official report, column 1286). The site was decommissioned in 2018 however, there is continuing Defence requirement for the adjacent training area (Ballykinler Training Centre).</p><p>In February 2019, the Ministry of Defence also confirmed its use of Newtownards Airfield in Northern Ireland had ceased.</p><p>The Department's intent remains to dispose of Kinnegar Logistics Base; plans to vacate the site are still being developed.</p>","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Anne-Marie Trevelyan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144752/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T15:12:45.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144752/answer","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144752/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-09-04","Military Bases: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent progress has been made on disposing of (a) Abercorn barracks and (b) other earmarked sites in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","286775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144753","Department for Transport","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Government is encouraging the production and use of sustainable alternative aviation fuels in the UK. Recent changes to the Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation (RTFO) mean that renewable aviation fuels are eligible for reward, in the form of tradeable certificates.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, the Future Fuels for Flight and Freight Competition (the F4C) makes up to £20 million of capital funding available to projects that will produce low carbon waste-based fuels to be used in aeroplanes and lorries.</p><p><em> </em></p><p>The Government welcomes the aviation sector’s positive progress in responding to the challenge of addressing its impact on climate change, including through new and innovative projects to convert waste to jet fuel. As the new Minister of State for the Future of Transport, I am actively considering further policies that the Government can put in place to assist the long-term uptake of sustainable alternative fuels in this sector.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144753/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T11:39:43.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144753/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144753/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-09-04","Aviation: Renewable Fuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will set targets for the proportion of aviation fuel required to be sustainable sources; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","286606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144754","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-09-09","<p>If agreement is not reached on carry-over the Government will look to reintroduce Bills in the next session, and details on this will be set out in the Queen’s Speech.</p><p> </p><p>Introducing a new Agriculture Bill in the next session is an opportunity to reflect on the scrutiny of the House of Commons and improve the legislation that will underpin our new domestic agriculture policy.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144754/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T14:30:02.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144754/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144754/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-09-04","Agriculture Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will ensure that the Agriculture Bill is carried over into the next session of Parliament.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","286776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144755","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-09-09","<p>Fuel Services for visiting business aviation flights at RAF Northolt are provided by a contract with World Fuels Group. Therefore decisions on the future availability of sustainable aviation fuel would require contract modification agreement between World Fuels and the Ministry of Defence. There are currently no plans in this regard. All fuel provided must comply with regulatory standards.</p>","Plymouth, Moor View","Johnny Mercer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144755/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T16:14:22.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144755/answer","Biography information for Johnny Mercer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144755/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-09-04","RAF Northolt: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will encourage commercial flights using RAF Northolt to use sustainable sources of aviation fuel.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","286607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144756","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-09-09","<p>For the position on the Type 31 Frigate programme, I refer the hon. Member to the answer my predecessor gave to the hon. Member for Birkenhead (Frank Field) on 13 May 2019 to Question 251904.</p><p>In respect of the Fleet Solid Support ships, subject to normal approvals, we anticipate that a design and build contract will be awarded in 2020. An announcement will be made in due course.</p>","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Anne-Marie Trevelyan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144756/answer","Hansard Extract , Wednesday 8 May 2019, UIN  251904.docx","Hansard Extract , Wednesday 8 May 2019, UIN  251904.docx","Type 31 Frigates: Procurement","Type 31 Frigates: Procurement",,"2019-09-09T15:10:29.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144756/answer","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144756/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-09-04","Warships: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he will announce preferred bidders for (a) Type 31e frigates and (b) fleet solid support ships.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","286777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144757","Home Office","false","2019-09-09","<p>Much of our national security cooperation with our European partners takes place outside the EU structures and so is not dependent on our membership. We continue to work intensively with operational partners to ensure that we are ready for any eventuality.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144757/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T15:10:16.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144757/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144757/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-09-04","Disclosure of Information: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the implications for national security should cross-border data sharing with the EU end as a result of the UK leaving the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","286723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144758","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Department does not record mortality rates or information on the causes of benefit claimants’ deaths, as there is no causal relationship between somebody claiming a benefit and their death.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has been clear that leaving the EU with a deal is its preferred option. The Government is, however, continuing to plan for a range of scenarios, including a no deal exit from the EU. These contingencies ensure that DWP can continue to provide our vital services and that individuals will continue to be able to access DWP benefits and services on the same basis as they do now.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144758/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T10:40:42.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144758/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144758/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-09-04","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate she has made of the potential (a) mortality rate and (b) number of suicides among benefit claimants in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","286724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144759","Department for International Development","false","2019-09-09","<p>As one of the largest donors to the Global Partnership for Education (GPE), DFID is helping to ensure that children in Kenya have access to high quality education. GPE supports the Government of Kenya to develop national education sector plans, improve early grade mathematics and strengthen school management systems. Through UK support to the Girls’ Education Challenge, we are also improving learning opportunities and outcomes for Kenya’s most marginalised girls.</p><p> </p><p>In partnership with the Kenyan Ministry of Education in 2015, DFID provided funding to rigorously test a new structured approach to early grade teaching. The approach helped teachers better meet the needs of all students, provided continual coaching and monitoring, and improved teaching materials. The Kenyan Government scaled the approach nationwide. Independent research shows this reform led to the percentage of grade two children meeting learning benchmarks in English rising from 34% to 65%.</p>","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144759/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T15:45:03.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144759/answer","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144759/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-09-04","Kenya: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that children in Kenya have access to high quality education.","false","Biography information for Stephen Twigg","Liverpool, West Derby","Stephen Twigg","286602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144760","Treasury","false","2019-09-09","<p>In the latest spending round we have increased the resource funding available to the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government for 2020/21 by 2.7% to deliver their priorities, including delivering the homes this country needs in the right places. As part of this settlement, MHCLG’s admin budget will increase from £258m in 2019/20 to £341m in 2020/21, within which funding for Homes England will also increase. This will enable them to continue delivering significant investment in housing, with at least £44bn of financial support committed at the Autumn Budget 2017 over a five-year period, and to support the Government’s overall ambition of 300,000 additional homes on average by the mid-2020s.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144760/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T09:36:46.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144760/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144760/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-09-04","Homes England: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to his oral statement of 4 September 2019 on Spending Round 2019, how much funding he plans to allocate to Homes England to deliver more homes where people need them; how many homes are planned to be built and what the location will be of those homes.","false","Biography information for Sarah Jones","Croydon Central","Sarah Jones","286842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144761","Department for International Development","false","2019-09-09","<p>DFID is helping to improve life opportunities and learning outcomes for the most vulnerable girls in Kenya including those who are pregnant, through our £154 million Girls Education Challenge (GEC) programme. Through investments in catch up classes, financial assistance, and support for life skills and confidence building, GEC is supporting girls who are pregnant and young mothers, to re-enter education.</p>","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144761/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T15:46:01.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144761/answer","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144761/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-09-04","Kenya: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps he is taking to ensure that girls in Kenya who become pregnant are able to re-enter education.","false","Biography information for Stephen Twigg","Liverpool, West Derby","Stephen Twigg","286603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144762","Department for International Development","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Secretary of State has not yet had the opportunity to meet representatives of the Kenyan Government.</p><p>DFID officials continue to discuss the importance of inclusive education with senior representatives at the Ministry of Education, although DFID has not been consulted on the draft National Re-entry Guidelines for Learners in Basic Education. DFID support through the Global Partnership for Education and the Girls’ Education Challenge Fund helps to improve access to education and learning for the most vulnerable children, including support for re-entry.</p>","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144762/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T15:46:53.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144762/answer","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144762/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-09-04","Kenya: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions he has had with the Kenyan Government on the implementation of the National Re-entry Guidelines for Learners in Basic Education.","false","Biography information for Stephen Twigg","Liverpool, West Derby","Stephen Twigg","286604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144763","Treasury","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Spending Round confirmed that the Government will provide £24m of additional funding for the Building Safety Programme in 2020/21 to help prevent a tragedy like Grenfell happening again. The Government has announced that £10m of this funding will be available to support the Protection Board who will provide expert, tailored building checks and inspections, if necessary, on all high-risk residential buildings in England by 2021. The remaining funding will be used to support the new building safety regime.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144763/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T09:39:55.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144763/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144763/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-09-04","Buildings: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to his oral statement of 4 September 2019 entitled, Spending Round 2019, to what programmes will the £24 million additional funding for the Building Safety Programme to support the new building safety regime be allocated.","false","Biography information for Sarah Jones","Croydon Central","Sarah Jones","286843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144764","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-09-09","<p>It is the responsibility of individual employers to ensure that their employees are appropriately trained and competent to carry out their duties. Individual regulated healthcare professionals also need to undertake continuous professional development in order to maintain their registration.</p><p>The Online Harms White Paper will make the internet safer for everyone. The Department will continue to work with social media companies to address wider issues of the impact of the internet on mental health and wellbeing.</p>","Mid Bedfordshire","Ms Nadine Dorries","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144764/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T17:33:50.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144764/answer","Biography information for Ms Nadine Dorries","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144764/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-04","Euthanasia: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to ensure mental health professionals are (a) informed about and (b) equipped to deal with the potential harms of (a) euthanasia websites and (b) similar online media on vulnerable people under their care.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","286684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144765","Treasury","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Spending Round confirmed that the Government will provide £24m of additional funding for the Building Safety Programme in 2020/21 to help prevent a tragedy like Grenfell happening again. Further to this, the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government confirmed that an additional £4m of funding will be made available in 2019/20 to support LAs in the data collection exercise on external wall systems in high rise buildings.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144765/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T09:43:38.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144765/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144765/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-09-04","Buildings: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to his oral statement of 4 September 2019 entitled, Spending Round 2019, what proportion of the £24 million additional funding for the Building Safety Programme to support the new building safety regime will be provided to (a) local authorities and (b) housing associations to support the data collection exercise on external wall systems in high rise buildings.","false","Biography information for Sarah Jones","Croydon Central","Sarah Jones","286844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144766","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-09-09","<p>The National Autistic Society estimates that around 70-80% of autistic people will develop a mental health condition at some point in their lives. It is therefore critical that autistic people have equitable access to mental health services, with reasonable adjustments made where appropriate.</p><p>On 5 December 2018, the Government announced that we will be launching a comprehensive review of our autism strategy, ‘Think Autism’. This is to ensure it remains fit for purpose. The Government wants an autism strategy that works for all autistic people, and that is why, working very closely with the Department for Education, the Department of Health and Social Care will be extending the strategy to include children.</p><p>To inform our review we launched a national call for evidence, which closed on 16 May. This will help us understand what is working and where we need to push harder to transform experiences of autistic people. We will be considering the evidence in respect of mental health services as part of this and we will be publishing the revised strategy later this year.</p><p>In March 2018, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) updated their existing guideline and Quality Standard on diagnosing and managing attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) in adults, young people and children. NICE has established an expert working group to look at how the current NICE guidance and quality standard on ADHD are being implemented. It is working to identify best practice and examples of innovation, which have improved outcomes for people with ADHD, so that these can be widely disseminated to commissioners to improve local practice.</p><p><br> Under the NHS Long Term Plan, there will be a comprehensive expansion of mental health services, with an additional £2.3 billion in real terms by 2023/24. This will give 380,000 more adults access to psychological therapies and 345,000 more children and young people greater support in the next five years. The National Health Service will also roll out new waiting times to ensure rapid access to mental health services in the community for those that need it and expand crisis care.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144766/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T18:17:44.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144766/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144766/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-04","Autism and Hyperactivity: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of introducing tailored mental health services for people diagnosed with (a) autism and (b) ADHD.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","286685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144767","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-09-09","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to the hon. Member in the time available before Prorogation.</p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144767/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T16:37:00.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144767/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144767/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-04","Prescriptions: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will (a) review the list of medical conditions for which patients are exempt from prescription charges and (b) ensure that (i) multiple sclerosis and (ii) other long-term illnesses are included on that list.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","286686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144768","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-09-09","<p>Yes, we expect to be able to publish research findings in the autumn.</p>","Tatton","Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144768/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T15:23:17.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144768/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144768/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-09-04","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 15 May 2019 to Question 252655, on Buildings: Insulation, if he will publish the results of the tests.","false","Biography information for Sarah Jones","Croydon Central","Sarah Jones","286845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144769","Department for Transport","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Government is actively supporting the development of innovative technology in aviation including automation. We supported a Global Urban Air Summit held at Farnborough last week which brought together industry, academia and government to discuss the development of new technologies like electric and autonomous aircraft.</p><p> </p><p>The Transport Secretary met a range of aviation stakeholders at the Light Aircraft Association Rally. In addition Ministers from the Department of Business, Energy and Industrial Challenge meet regularly with the Aerospace Industry through the Aerospace Growth Partnership.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144769/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T12:50:33.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144769/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144769/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-09-04","Aerospace Industry: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions (a) he, (b) Ministers in his Department and (c) officials of his Department have had with representatives of the aerospace industry on the the potential benefits of the use of autonomous technology.","false","Biography information for Jack Lopresti","Filton and Bradley Stoke","Jack Lopresti","286695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144770","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-09-09","<p>The United Kingdom will be leaving the European Union on 31 October whatever the circumstances. We would prefer to leave with a deal. The details of this partnership, including participation in the European Reference Networks, will be a matter for negotiation with the EU after we leave. We are preparing for that negotiation and will work with a wide range of partners to ensure a successful outcome for UK business and citizens.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144770/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T16:14:56.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144770/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144770/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-04","European Reference Networks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether the UK will be excluded from European Reference Networks when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mohammad Yasin","Bedford","Mohammad Yasin","286820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144771","Department for Transport","false","2019-09-09","<p>Ministers and officials across Government regularly meet with the aviation and aerospace sectors to discuss proposals for decarbonisation. The Government is considering further policies it can put in place to assist the long-term development of innovative technology such as electric propulsion.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Government recently supported a Global Urban Air Summit held at Farnborough Airport, which brought together industry and academia to discuss the development of new technologies like electric and autonomous aircraft. The Transport Secretary also met a range of aviation stakeholders at the Light Aircraft Association Rally.</p><p> </p><p>I am actively meeting industry leaders to explore new ways to promote transport innovation.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144771/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T12:56:52.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144771/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144771/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-09-04","Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport,what discussions (a) he, (b) Ministers of his Department and (c) officials in his Department have had with representatives of the aviation industry on the potential for reductions in the level of (i) emissions and (ii) noise as a result of electric propulsion.","false","Biography information for Jack Lopresti","Filton and Bradley Stoke","Jack Lopresti","286696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144772","Department for Transport","false","2019-09-09","<p>Government Ministers and officials are in frequent dialogue with the motor industry as we work together to deliver our ambition for zero emission road transport. Most recently I was delighted to speak and meet with industry representatives at ‘Cenex LCV2019’ the UK’s premier electric vehicle and technology showcase, held at Millbrook on 04 September 2019.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144772/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T13:00:23.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144772/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144772/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-09-04","Electric Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions (a) he, (b) Ministers of his Department and (c) officials in his Department have had with representatives of the motor industry on the potential reduction in vehicle emissions from electric powered propulsion.","false","Biography information for Jack Lopresti","Filton and Bradley Stoke","Jack Lopresti","286697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144773","Cabinet Office","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Cabinet Office does not hold data on the number of citizens on the register, as local authorities manage their registers.</p><p>Whilst we cannot provide data for individual constituencies, we are able to provide the number of applications that were submitted through the Individual Electoral Registration Digital Service (IER DS) for North Lanarkshire and Scotland, each day between 27 August<br>2019 to 4 September 2019, as shown below.</p><p>These figures are for the total number of applications that have been made to the IER DS. Not all individuals who submit an application to register to vote are necessarily added to the electoral register. Eligibility to be added to a register is determined by Electoral Registration Officers for their local areas.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Date</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>North Lanarkshire</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Scotland</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>27/08/2019</p></td><td><p>168</p></td><td><p>2160</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>28/08/2019</p></td><td><p>108</p></td><td><p>2544</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>29/08/2019</p></td><td><p>106</p></td><td><p>2514</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>30/08/2019</p></td><td><p>76</p></td><td><p>1706</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31/08/2019</p></td><td><p>35</p></td><td><p>1379</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01/09/2019</p></td><td><p>47</p></td><td><p>991</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>02/09/2019</p></td><td><p>89</p></td><td><p>4055</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>03/09/2019</p></td><td><p>161</p></td><td><p>4564</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>04/09/2019</p></td><td><p>164</p></td><td><p>4494</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>790</p></td><td><p>19913</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p>","Torbay","Kevin Foster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144773/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T14:43:05.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144773/answer","Biography information for Kevin Foster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144773/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-09-04","Electoral Register: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people registered to vote each day between 27 August 2019 to 4 September 2019 in (a) the Motherwell and Wishaw constituency, (b) North Lanarkshire and (c) Scotland.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","286810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144774","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-09-09","<p>In July, Government asked local authorities and housing associations to complete a data collection exercise on the external wall systems of high-rise residential buildings that are 18 metres or above. New Burdens funding will be available to local authorities to help them fulfil this exercise. The Government is clear that building owners are responsible for the safety of their buildings and should act to address any safety issues they identify.</p>","Tatton","Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144774/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T15:17:39.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144774/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144774/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-09-04","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 23 July 2019 to Question 279061, on Buildings: Insulation, whether his Department has plans to allocate funding to (a) local authorities and (b) housing associations to (i) identify and (b) remediate unsafe HPL systems on their buildings.","false","Biography information for Sarah Jones","Croydon Central","Sarah Jones","286846"
