"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144342","Department for International Trade","false","2019-09-05","<p>Licensing data is published as Official Statistics on GOV.UK. It covers only licensing information for the whole of the UK. Regional and constituency data can only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p>Currently only information from Q1 2019 (1 January to 31 March 2019) has been published; this shows 3,343 export licence applications were received and 3,298 export licences were issued.</p><p>The department’s performance targets are for 70% of applications for Standard Individual Export Licences (SIELs) to be responded to within 20 working days, and 99% within 60 working days. The targets apply as soon as the applicant has supplied the full documentation necessary to support their application. The median processing time for SIELs in Q1 2019 was 11 working days. Data covering the period 1 April 2019 to 30 June 2019 will be published on 15 October 2019.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144342/answer",,,,,"286241 ; 286242","2019-09-05T11:18:34.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144342/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144342/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-09-03","Export Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many export licence requests have been received by her Department from businesses in (a) the UK, (b) the North East and (c) Wansbeck constituency in 2019.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","286240"
