"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144359","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-09-09","<p><em>It has not proved possible to respond to the hon. Member in the time available before Prorogation.</em></p>","Boston and Skegness","Matt Warman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144359/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T13:42:58.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144359/answer","Biography information for Matt Warman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144359/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-09-03","YouTube: Disinformation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if she will make an assessment of the potential effect of YouTube’s recommendation algorithm and misinformation on public health in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","286177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144360","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Department continues to monitor and analyse overall staffing levels in the health and social care sectors and we have been monitoring leaver and joiner rates of European Union staff on a regular basis since the 2016 referendum. We are not complacent and have plans in place to ensure there will continue to be sufficient staff to deliver the high-quality services on which the public relies. Our overall programme of work is comprehensive, thorough and continuously updated and will stand irrespective of the terms in which the United Kingdom leaves the EU.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144360/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T17:02:39.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144360/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144360/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-03","NHS and Social Services: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment he has made of the effect on levels of staffing in (a) NHS bodies, (b) care homes, and (c) other social care services of a potential decrease in net migration from other EU countries in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","286178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144361","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Department is working with its partners across Government, arm’s length bodies, local authorities, industry and the wider health and care system to ensure that all relevant parties are prepared for exiting the European Union. The quality and safety of patient care is paramount in our preparedness plans.</p><p> </p><p>The Department, alongside NHS England and NHS Improvement, is ensuring that there is regular communication with frontline National Health Service organisations and stakeholders in the health and social care sector regarding EU Exit preparations. NHS England will be holding EU Exit Roadshows in the lead up to 31 October, building on the regular communication that the Department and NHS England has with the frontline.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144361/answer",,,,,"285035 ; 285316 ; 286180 ; 286181","2019-09-09T14:58:33.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144361/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144361/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-03","Department of Health and Social Care: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent discussions his Department has had with (a) the Local Government Association, (b) London Councils, (c) the Mayor of London and (d) the London Borough of Newham on preparedness in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a deal on 31 October 2019.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","286179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144362","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Department is working with its partners across Government, arm’s length bodies, local authorities, industry and the wider health and care system to ensure that all relevant parties are prepared for exiting the European Union. The quality and safety of patient care is paramount in our preparedness plans.</p><p> </p><p>The Department, alongside NHS England and NHS Improvement, is ensuring that there is regular communication with frontline National Health Service organisations and stakeholders in the health and social care sector regarding EU Exit preparations. NHS England will be holding EU Exit Roadshows in the lead up to 31 October, building on the regular communication that the Department and NHS England has with the frontline.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144362/answer",,,,,"285035 ; 285316 ; 286179 ; 286181","2019-09-09T14:58:33.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144362/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144362/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-03","Department of Health and Social Care: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what support his Department has made available to (a) the Mayor of London, and (b) the London Borough of Newham on preparedness in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a deal on 31 October 2019.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","286180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144363","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Department is working with its partners across Government, arm’s length bodies, local authorities, industry and the wider health and care system to ensure that all relevant parties are prepared for exiting the European Union. The quality and safety of patient care is paramount in our preparedness plans.</p><p> </p><p>The Department, alongside NHS England and NHS Improvement, is ensuring that there is regular communication with frontline National Health Service organisations and stakeholders in the health and social care sector regarding EU Exit preparations. NHS England will be holding EU Exit Roadshows in the lead up to 31 October, building on the regular communication that the Department and NHS England has with the frontline.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144363/answer",,,,,"285035 ; 285316 ; 286179 ; 286180","2019-09-09T14:58:33.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144363/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144363/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-03","Health Services: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment he has made of the potential  effect of the UK leaving the EU without a deal on 31 October 2019 on the ability of the (a) Greater London Authority and (b) London Borough of Newham to provide services to the public.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","286181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144364","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-09-09","<p>Comparisons between entitlement in legacy benefits and Universal Credit fail to reflect that, until recently, people only claimed Universal Credit as a result of a change in their circumstances.</p><p>It is important to remember that there are £2.4 billion of unclaimed benefits not going to the people who need them because they are unaware of how to claim, or that they may be entitled. Universal Credit makes sure that welfare payments reach those who need them most, and when we complete moving legacy benefit claimants over to Universal Credit, an estimated 700,000 more people will get paid their full entitlement because of Universal Credit.</p><p>The Government have committed to spending in excess of £3 billion over 10 years on transitional protection for 1.1 million households. This will help fund assistance for those moving from Housing Benefit to Universal Credit including a two week ‘transitional housing payment’. We are also introducing a two-week run on for eligible claimants of Income Support, Jobseeker’s Allowance and Employment and Support Allowance from July 2020.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Colchester","Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144364/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T10:47:37.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144364/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144364/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-09-03","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate her Department has made of the proportion of social security claimants who will receive less money once they have migrated to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","286277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144365","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Single Electricity Market (SEM) is an example of North-South cooperation that has benefited the consumers and economies of Northern Ireland and Ireland. Therefore it is the Government’s position that by far the best outcome for electricity in Northern Ireland is to maintain the Single Electricity Market, including in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a Withdrawal Agreement. The UK will continue to work with the Irish Government to seek to ensure the Single Electricity Market will continue following Exit.</p>","Spelthorne","Kwasi Kwarteng","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144365/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T07:24:47.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144365/answer","Biography information for Kwasi  Kwarteng","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144365/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-09-03","Energy: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Government plans to maintain the Single Energy Area for Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a Withdrawal Agreement on 31 October 2019.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","286278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144366","Home Office","false","2019-09-09","<p>The day-to-day management of digital forensic services is an operational matter for the police. The Home Office is funding the police-led Transforming Forensics Programme, which will establish a Forensic Capability Network (FCN) to support police forces to manage commercial, quality and scientific issues in forensics.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144366/answer",,,,,"286183","2019-09-09T14:13:46.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144366/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144366/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-09-03","Metropolitan Police: Forensic Science","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of digital forensics capacity within the Metropolitan Police Service.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","286182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144367","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Government announced the review of the legal aid means test on 7 February 2019, as part of the Legal Support Action Plan.</p><p>The review will consider the full range of means-testing criteria including the applicable thresholds for legal aid entitlement and their interaction with wider criteria.</p><p>The review is in progress, bringing together data, evidence and expertise, and liaising with experts from across the field to explore potential improvements to the system.</p><p>This comprehensive review of the legal aid eligibility regime is expected to conclude in summer 2020 after which we will publish a full consultation paper setting out our future policy on the proposals in this area. We will seek to implement any final recommendations as soon as practicable following public consultation.</p>","Aldridge-Brownhills","Wendy Morton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144367/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T15:10:37.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144367/answer","Biography information for Wendy Morton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144367/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-09-03","Legal Aid Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent progress his Department has made in reviewing the legal aid means test.","false","Biography information for Faisal Rashid","Warrington South","Faisal Rashid","286365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144368","Cabinet Office","false","2019-09-09","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to the hon. Member in the time available before Prorogation.</p>","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144368/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T16:45:25.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144368/answer","Biography information for Simon Hart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144368/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-09-03","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, what his Department's three highest policy priorities are in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a withdrawal agreement.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","286279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144369","Home Office","false","2019-09-09","<p>The day-to-day management of digital forensic services is an operational matter for the police. The Home Office is funding the police-led Transforming Forensics Programme, which will establish a Forensic Capability Network (FCN) to support police forces to manage commercial, quality and scientific issues in forensics.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144369/answer",,,,,"286182","2019-09-09T14:13:46.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144369/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144369/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-09-03","Metropolitan Police: Forensic Science","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an assessment of the adequacy of digital forensics capacity within the Metropolitan Police Service on the a) progress of investigations, and b) charge rate.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","286183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144370","Wales Office","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Prime Minister announced in his speech on 27 July that the Government will bring forward plans on the UK Shared Prosperity Fund. We will consult on the design of the fund and welcome input from across the UK.</p><p>The UK Shared Prosperity Fund will invest in the foundations of productivity as set out in our modern Industrial Strategy to support people to benefit from economic prosperity, especially in those parts of the UK whose economies are furthest behind.</p><p>In the meantime, stakeholders can continue to invest with confidence and certainty. The Government has guaranteed that if we leave the EU without a deal, we will continue to fund all European and Structural Investment Funds projects that would have been funded by the EU under the 2014-2020 programme period.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144370/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T12:20:46.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144370/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144370/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2019-09-03","UK Shared Prosperity Fund: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, whether the Shared Prosperity Fund will be open to Welsh applications by 31 October 2019.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","286280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144371","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-09-09","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to the Hon. Member in the time available before Prorogation.</p><p> </p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144371/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T17:02:44.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144371/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144371/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-09-03","Brexit: Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many formal meetings (a) he or (b) Departmental officials have had with representatives of the EU since the Rt hon. Member for Uxbridge and Ruslip became Prime Minister.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","286281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144372","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-09-09","<p>Nobody has to wait for five weeks for a payment following an application for Universal Credit (UC).</p><p> </p><p>UC new claim advances provide access to a payment for those in financial need, which can be accessed urgently, until their first regular UC payment is due. Claimants can access up to 100% of the total expected monthly award, for which they can pay back over a period of up to 12 months.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has taken a number of steps to ensure that advances meet the needs of claimants and that recovery arrangements are personalised and reasonable. The maximum rate of deductions cannot normally exceed 40 per cent of the UC standard allowance and does not reduce other components of an award, such as money paid for children, housing or when someone is caring for a severely disabled person. From October 2019 this will be reduced to 30 per cent and from October 2021 we are increasing the maximum recovery period for advances from 12 to 16 months.</p><p> </p><p>This is just one of a number of measures the Department has put in place to support claimants such as paying those claimants moving from Housing Benefit to UC a two week ‘transitional housing payment’. We are also introducing a two-week run on for eligible claimants of Income Support, Jobseeker’s Allowance and Employment and Support Allowance from July 2020.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144372/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T15:32:16.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144372/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144372/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-09-03","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what options her Department is considering to reduce the five week waiting time for universal credit claimants.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","286082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144373","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-09-09","<p>The proportion of private market rents that are at or below the LHA rate for (a) one and (b) two bedroom accommodation for each region in England and Wales are set out below. This is based on:</p><ul><li>2019/20 LHA rates published here <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/local-housing-allowance-lha-rates-applicable-from-april-2019-to-march-2020" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/local-housing-allowance-lha-rates-applicable-from-april-2019-to-march-2020</a></li></ul><ul><li>Valuation Office Agency data <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/local-housing-allowance-list-of-rents" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/local-housing-allowance-list-of-rents</a></li></ul><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>1 Bed</p></td><td><p>2 Bed</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>17%</p></td><td><p>17%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Eastern</p></td><td><p>9%</p></td><td><p>9%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North East</p></td><td><p>26%</p></td><td><p>25%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>23%</p></td><td><p>22%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>10%</p></td><td><p>10%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>14%</p></td><td><p>14%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>16%</p></td><td><p>14%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorks &amp; the Humber</p></td><td><p>20%</p></td><td><p>21%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wales</p></td><td><p>22%</p></td><td><p>22%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Colchester","Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144373/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T15:43:34.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144373/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144373/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-09-03","Local Housing Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment has been made of the affordability of (a) one and (b) two bedroom properties for Local Housing Allowance claimants in each region of England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","286083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144374","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-09-09","<p>In May 2019, 54,000 (3%) Universal Credit payments were subject to a deduction for council tax arrears.</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p> </p><ol><li>The number of deductions is rounded to the nearest 1000</li><li>The proportion is rounded to the nearest %</li></ol><p><strong> </strong></p>","Colchester","Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144374/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T16:02:32.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144374/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144374/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-09-03","Universal Credit: Deductions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of universal credit payments were subject to a deduction for council tax arrears.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","286084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144375","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Secretary of State is bound by law to complete an annual review of benefit and pension rates to determine whether they have retained their value in relation to the general level of prices or - in the case of the full rate of the new State Pension, basic State Pension and Standard Minimum Guarantee (SMG) in Pension Credit - earnings.</p><p> </p><p>Where prices and earnings have increased relative to the value of those benefits or pensions, the Secretary of State must increase non-contributory benefits for additional disability needs and for carers, as well as Additional Pension, at least in line with the increase in prices. In the case of the basic and the full rate of the new State Pension, the triple lock guarantees that rates will be raised by the highest of the rise in prices, the rise in earnings, or 2.5% for the duration of this Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State must also consider the rates of other benefits including working age benefits, and may decide to increase those at her discretion taking into account considerations such as the prevailing national economic circumstances and Government priorities at that time. She will make her assessment later this year and announce it ahead of the up-rating of benefits in April 2020. From that date she is able to implement a discretionary decision since the four-year freeze set by the Welfare Reform &amp; Work Act 2016 will have lapsed.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144375/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T16:23:56.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144375/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144375/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-09-03","Social Security Benefits: Uprating","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of uprating benefits by CPI plus 2 per cent over the next four years, and will she make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","286085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144376","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-09-09","<p>An Impact Assessment of the benefit freeze was published in 2015, this is available in the link below.</p><p><a href="https://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006C.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006C.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>This benefit freeze excluded Disability Living Allowance, Personal Independence Payment, Attendance Allowance, the Support Group component of Employment and Support Allowance (for those not expected to look for work), disability premia in working-age benefits and the disabled elements of tax credits. This provides protection for those facing the additional cost of disability.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144376/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T10:47:35.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144376/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144376/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-09-03","Social Security Benefits: Chronic Illnesses and Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment she has made of the effect of the working age benefit freeze on people with (a) disabilities and (b) long term health conditions.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","286086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144377","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-09-09","<p>Through the annual Estates Return Information Collection, data is collected annually on the number of incidents caused by estates and infrastructure failure which resulted in clinical services being delayed, cancelled or otherwise interfered with owing to problems or failures related to the estates and infrastructure failure. For National Health Service trusts and NHS foundation trusts, the data available is shown in the following table.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of clinical service incidents caused by estates and infrastructure failure</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>256</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>97</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>841</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>This data was not collected before 2015/16.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144377/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T14:22:19.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144377/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144377/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-03","Hospitals: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many clinical service incidents caused by estates and infrastructure failure were recorded by NHS trusts and foundation trusts within NHS North West in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir George Howarth","Knowsley","Sir George Howarth","286110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144378","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-09-09","<p>No estimate has been made of the cost of the Defence Nuclear Enterprise for calendar year 2019. Information on forecast costs for financial years 2018/19 and 2019/20 can be found in figure 12 of the National Audit Office's landscape review of the Enterprise published on 22 May 2018, which is available at the following link:</p><p>https://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/The-Defence-Nuclear-Enterprise-a-landscape-review.pdf</p><p>The Ministry of Defence does not, and has no plans to, routinely publish whole life costs for projects, nuclear or otherwise, beyond what is already published in reports such as the Defence Equipment Plan, Ministry of Defence Annual Report and Accounts, and the Infrastructure and Projects Authority's Annual Report on Major Projects.</p>","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Anne-Marie Trevelyan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144378/answer",,,,,,"2019-09-09T16:13:58.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144378/answer","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144378/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-09-03","Trident","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he he has made of the cost to the public purse of maintaining the Trident Nuclear Weapons programme for (a) 2019 and (b) the lifetime of that programme.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","286283"
